#: tuning_tuned.xml:1097
#, no-c-format
msgid "modules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1099
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>modules</literal> plug-in manages kernel modules within the "
"profiles. It can load or unload specific modules when a profile is "
"activated, allowing administrators to optimize system behavior for different "
"workloads by controlling which kernel modules are active. When this plug-in "
"is used, &tunedapp; writes information about the kernel modules in the "
"<filename>/etc/modprobe.d/tuned.conf</filename> file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1107
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you need to add a kernel module parameter that should be handled by "
"&tuned;, include it in the profile configuration using the following syntax:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1111
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[modules]\n"
"<replaceable>MODULE_NAME</replaceable>=<replaceable>MODULE_PARAMETERS</"
"replaceable><co xml:id=\"module-parameters\"/>\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1117
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can mention multiple module parameters separated by comma."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1122
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you want the module to be reloaded automatically, use the <literal>+r</"
"literal> option:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1126
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[modules]\n"
"<replaceable>MODULE_NAME</replaceable>=+r,<replaceable>MODULE_PARAMETERS</"
"replaceable>\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1130
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1134
#, no-c-format
msgid "Automatic reload of kernel modules by &tunedapp;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1135
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[modules]\n"
"cpufreq_conservative=+r,down_threshold=20,up_threshold=80,"
"sampling_rate=20000 <co xml:id=\"cpu-conservative-r\"/>\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1144
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>cpufreq_conservative</parameter> is a kernel module that adjusts "
"the CPU clock speed based on the system load. It is more conservative in its "
"frequency scaling compared to other governors like <literal>ondemand</"
"literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1152
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>=+r</literal> syntax indicates that the module should be loaded "
"if it is not already, and &tunedapp; keeps track of how many profiles are "
"using this module. When a module with <literal>+r</literal> is loaded, "
"&tunedapp; increments the reference count for this module. If the profile is "
"later deactivated, the reference count is decremented. The module is "
"unloaded only when the reference count reaches zero, which implies that no "
"other active profile is using it."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1163
#, no-c-format
msgid "The parameters mean the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1168
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>down_threshold=20</parameter> indicate that when the CPU usage "
"drops below 20%, the governor lowers the CPU frequency to conserve power."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1174
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>up_threshold=80</parameter> indicate that when the CPU usage "
"exceeds 80%, the governor raises the CPU frequency to improve performance."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1181
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>sampling_rate=20000</parameter> indicate that the governor "
"samples the CPU usage every 20,000 microseconds (or 20 milliseconds)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1191
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more information on kernel modules, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha-mod\"/"
"> . Additionally, you can check the parameters of the installed modules on "
"your system by looking at <filename>/sys/module/<replaceable>MODULE_NAME</"
"replaceable>/parameters/</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1200
#, no-c-format
msgid "cpu"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1202
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>cpu</literal> plug-in manages and optimizes CPU-related "
"settings to enhance performance, power savings, or a balance between the "
"two. This plug-in allows fine-grained control over how the CPU operates, "
"including setting the frequency governor, energy performance bias, and other "
"parameters that directly influence the CPU's behavior and performance "
"characteristics."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1209
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Certain commonly used parameters for the <literal>cpu</literal> plug-in are "
"as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1215
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>priority</parameter> : Sets the priority of CPU tuning "
"operations. Higher values give the tuning operation a higher priority."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1221
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>governor</parameter> : Sets the CPU frequency scaling governor. "
"Common options for this parameter include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1227
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>performance</literal> : Forces the CPU to run at the maximum "
"frequency, providing the best performance at the cost of higher power "
"consumption."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1234
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>ondemand</literal> : Dynamically adjusts the CPU frequency based on "
"system load, providing a balance between performance and power saving."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1240
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>conservative</literal> : Similar to the <literal>ondemand</literal> "
"governor, but increases or decreases the CPU frequency more gradually. It is "
"suitable for systems where power saving is important but performance should "
"still be maintained."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1250
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>energy_perf_bias</parameter> : Hints to the CPU how to balance "
"between power consumption and performance. Common options for this parameter "
"include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1257
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>performance</literal> : Bias towards maximum performance, possibly "
"increasing power consumption."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1263
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>powersave</literal> : Bias towards power saving, possibly reducing "
"performance."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1269
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>power</literal> : A more aggressive power-saving setting compared "
"to <literal>powersave</literal> , but potentially less demanding compared to "
"<literal>performance</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1276
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>normal</literal> : A balanced setting between performance and power "
"saving."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1284
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>force_latency</parameter> : Controls the forced latency setting "
"for the CPU. Lower values mean the system aggressively applies power-saving "
"measures, possibly at the cost of increased latency. Higher values reduce "
"the aggressiveness of power-saving measures, possibly improving "
"responsiveness."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1292
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>min_perf_pct</parameter> : Specifies the minimum performance "
"level as a percentage of the CPU's maximum performance. For example, a value "
"of 100 means the CPU always runs at its maximum performance level. Lower "
"values allow the CPU to run at lower performance levels when full "
"performance is not needed, which can save power."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1301
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, a profile created for CPU-intensive workload, such as high-"
"performance computing, can configure the plug-in for maximum CPU usage:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1306
#, no-c-format
msgid "&tunedapp; plug-in configuration for CPU-intensive workload"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1307
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[cpu]\n"
"priority=1\n"
"governor=performance\n"
"energy_perf_bias=performance\n"
"force_latency=10\n"
"min_perf_pct=100\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1316
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more information on CPU performance scaling, refer to <link xlink:"
"href=\"https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/admin-guide/pm/cpufreq.rst\"/"
"> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1323
#, no-c-format
msgid "audio"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1325
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>audio</literal> plug-in tunes the system to optimize audio "
"performance. This can involve adjusting CPU scheduling policies, setting CPU "
"affinity, and configuring other system parameters to minimize audio latency, "
"ensure smooth audio playback, and record real-time audio activities. For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1332
#, no-c-format
msgid "&tunedapp; plug-in configuration for optimal audio performance"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1333
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[audio]\n"
"timeout=10 <co xml:id=\"audio-plugin-timeout-parameter\"/>\n"
"reset_controller=False <co xml:id=\"audio-plugin-reset-controller-"
"parameter\"/>\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1341
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <parameter>timeout</parameter> parameter specifies the time period (in "
"seconds) for which the system should remain in the optimized state after the "
"last audio activity is detected. This is intended to prevent the system from "
"frequently switching back and forth between optimized and non-optimized "
"states, which can cause instability or glitches in audio performance."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1350
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <parameter>reset_controller</parameter> parameter manages the behavior "
"of the audio module's power-saving controller. It allows you to enable or "
"disable the resetting of the controller, which can influence how the system "
"handles power management for audio devices. The parameter interacts with a "
"system file located at <filename>/sys/module/<replaceable>AUDIO_MODULE_NAME</"
"replaceable>/parameters/power_save_controller</filename> (for example, "
"<filename>snd_hda_intel</filename> ). By default, it is set to "
"<literal>False</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1365
#, no-c-format
msgid "video"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1367
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>video</literal> plug-in provides options for tuning power-"
"saving settings for certain graphics cards, particularly AMD Radeon cards. "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1371
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[video]\n"
"radeon_powersave=dpm-balanced\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1375
#, no-c-format
msgid "Common parameters used with this plug-in are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1380
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>radeon_powersave</parameter> : This parameter controls the power-"
"saving mode of AMD Radeon graphics cards. It determines how the GPU handles "
"power management, impacting performance and energy consumption. "
"Configuration options used with this parameter include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1388
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>default</literal> : The default power-saving profile, which is the "
"default setting provided by the graphics driver."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1394
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>auto</literal> : Automatically adjusts power-saving settings based "
"on current system usage."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1400
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>low</literal> : A low-power profile that reduces performance to "
"save energy."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1406
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>mid</literal> : A medium-power profile that balances performance "
"and power savings."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1412
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>high</literal> : A high-power profile that maximizes performance at "
"the cost of higher power consumption."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1418
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>dynpm</literal> : Dynamic Power Management (DPM)&mdash;a mode that "
"allows for dynamic adjustments based on the workload."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1424
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>dpm-battery</literal> : A DPM profile optimized for battery usage."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1429
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>dpm-balanced</literal> : A DPM profile that balances performance "
"and power efficiency."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1435
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>dpm-performance</literal> : A DPM profile optimized for maximum "
"performance."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1446
#, no-c-format
msgid "disk"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1448
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>disk</literal> plug-in tunes and optimizes the performance and "
"power consumption of disk drives."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1452
#, no-c-format
msgid "Common parameters and their possible values are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1457
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>devices</parameter> : Specifies on which disk devices the tuning "
"parameters should be applied. By default, all devices are included. You can "
"specify devices separated by comma."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1464
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>dynamic</parameter> : Boolean values that enable or disable "
"dynamic tuning based on disk load. By default, it is set to <literal>True</"
"literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1470
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>elevator</parameter> : Configures the I/O scheduler (elevator) "
"for the disk. Depending on the system's available schedulers, the possible "
"options include <literal>noop</literal> , <literal>deadline</literal> or "
"<literal>cfq</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1478
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>apm</parameter> : An integer (1&ndash;254) that sets the Advanced "
"Power Management (APM) level of the disk. Higher values typically mean "
"better performance, but higher power consumption."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1485
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>spindown</parameter> : The integer value for the "
"<parameter>spindown</parameter> parameter is a special encoding used by the "
"<package>hdparm</package> utility to set the spin-down timeout for a disk. "
"For an explanation of the acceptable spin-down values, read about the "
"<option>-S</option> option in the man page of <package>hdparm</package> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1494
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>readahead</parameter> : An integer that sets the readahead value "
"for the disk in kilobytes. You can change this to sectors by adding the "
"appropriate suffix. For example, <literal>readahead = 8192 s</literal> . "
"Ensure there is at least one space between the number and the suffix."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1502
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>readahead_multiply</parameter> : A float value that indicates the "
"factor by which the value of the <parameter>readahead</parameter> parameter "
"is multiplied."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1509
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>scheduler_quantum</parameter> : An integer that sets the number "
"of I/O requests the scheduler handles simultaneously. Setting a higher "
"quantum can improve throughput for sequential I/O operations by allowing "
"more requests to be processed before switching. Conversely, a lower quantum "
"can improve responsiveness for random I/O operations by reducing latency."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1518
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"As an example, consider the following <literal>disk</literal> plug-in "
"configuration in a &tunedapp; profile:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1523
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>disk</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1524
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[disk]\n"
"# Comma separated list of devices, all devices if commented out.\n"
"devices=sda,sdb\n"
"\n"
"dynamic=True\n"
"elevator=deadline\n"
"apm=128\n"
"spindown=60\n"
"\n"
"# Readahead adjusted to sectors by specifying relevant suffix.\n"
"# There must be at least one space between the number and suffix.\n"
"readahead=8192 s\n"
"\n"
"readahead_multiply=1.5\n"
"scheduler_quantum=64\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1545
#, no-c-format
msgid "scsi_host"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1547
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>scsi_host</literal> plug-in is used to manage power-saving "
"settings for SCSI (Small Computer System Interface) host adapters on Linux "
"systems. Commonly used parameters for this plug-in include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1554
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>alpm</parameter> : The Aggressive Link Power Management (ALPM) "
"setting controls the power management policy for Serial ATA (SATA) links. It "
"can take different values to balance between power savings and performance. "
"The possible options for this parameter include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1562
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>min_power</literal> : This setting is more aggressive in terms of "
"power savings. It puts the system into a lower power state when the SATA "
"links are idle, which can save more power but may increase latency when "
"accessing the disks."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1570
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>medium_power</literal> : This setting provides a balance between "
"power savings and performance. It aims to reduce power consumption without "
"impacting system performance too much."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1577
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>max_performance</literal> : This setting keeps SCSI hosts and "
"devices in their highest power state. It prioritizes speed and "
"responsiveness over energy efficiency, disabling power-saving features to "
"minimize latency and maximize throughput."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1585
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, consider the following configuration that is appropriate for "
"battery-powered devices, low-usage servers, and systems with long idle "
"periods:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1589
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[scsi_host]\n"
"alpm=min_power\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1594
#, no-c-format
msgid "Read/write of link power management policy by &tunedapp;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1595
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The possible values are typically read from or written to the <filename>/sys/"
"class/scsi_host/<replaceable>SCSI_HOST_NAME</replaceable>/"
"link_power_management_policy</filename> file. The exact values may depend on "
"what the kernel and the hardware support."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1606
#, no-c-format
msgid "variables"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1608
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>variables</literal> plug-in allows for the definition of "
"variables that you can use across different &tunedapp; profiles. This is "
"particularly useful for setting parameters that may change based on the "
"system environment or user preferences. By centralizing variable "
"definitions, you can simplify profile management and enhance the flexibility "
"of your tuning configurations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1615
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Within the <literal>[variables]</literal> section of your profile "
"configuration, you can specify variables using the following methods:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1619
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[variables]\n"
"\n"
"include=<replaceable>PATH/TO/VARIABLE/CONFIGURATION/FILE</replaceable> <co "
"xml:id=\"variable-include\"/>\n"
"\n"
"<replaceable>VAR_NAME</replaceable>=<replaceable>value</replaceable> <co xml:"
"id=\"variable-value\"/>\n"
"\n"
"<replaceable>VAR_ANOTHER</replaceable>=${<replaceable>VAR_NAME_suffix</"
"replaceable>} <co xml:id=\"variable-variable\"/>\n"
"\n"
"<replaceable>VAR_DYNAMIC</replaceable>=$(uname -r) <co xml:id=\"variable-"
"command\"/>\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1632
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Include a configuration file that already contains variable definitions for "
"a certain context. For example, you can include the <filename>/etc/tuned/cpu-"
"partitioning-variables.conf</filename> file to make variables such as "
"<literal>isolated_cores</literal> and its values available for the ongoing "
"profile configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1641
#, no-c-format
msgid "Define a variable directly by assigning a value."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1646
#, no-c-format
msgid "Define a variable using another variable."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1651
#, no-c-format
msgid "Define a variable using a command output."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1656
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, consider the following configuration for variables and its "
"subsequent use in configuring other plug-ins for a profile configuration:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1661
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using dynamic variables for plug-in configurations in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1662
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[variables]\n"
"\n"
"include=/etc/tuned/cpu-partitioning-variables.conf\n"
"\n"
"SWAPPINESS_VALUE=10\n"
"NETWORK_INTERFACE=$(ip -o -4 route show to default | awk '{print $5}')\n"
"\n"
"[sysctl]\n"
"vm.swappiness=${SWAPPINESS_VALUE}\n"
"\n"
"[net]\n"
"interface=${NETWORK_INTERFACE}\n"
"disable_offload=yes\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1678
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more technically involved variable definitions, inspect the "
"<literal>[variables]</literal> plug-in configurations available in the "
"supported profile configuration files. To get a list of such profile "
"configuration paths where the <literal>[variables]</literal> plug-in is "
"included, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1684
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;<command>grep -r '\\[.*\\]' /usr/lib/tuned/*/tuned.conf | sort -"
"u | grep variables\n"
"</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1689
#, no-c-format
msgid "sysctl"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1691
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>sysctl</literal> plug-in offers a powerful way to customize "
"several kernel parameters at runtime. This allows system administrators to "
"optimize system performance, enhance security, and adjust network behavior "
"without directly editing system files or running manual sysctl commands."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1697
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>sysctl</literal> plug-in accepts a wide range of parameters. "
"Certain common categories include:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1703
#, no-c-format
msgid "Kernel parameters ( <parameter>kernel.*</parameter> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1708
#, no-c-format
msgid "Virtual Memory parameters ( <parameter>vm.*</parameter> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1713
#, no-c-format
msgid "Network parameters ( <parameter>net.*</parameter> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1718
#, no-c-format
msgid "File system parameters ( <parameter>fs.*</parameter> )"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1723
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"where <literal>*</literal> is the wild card expression denoting permissible "
"parameters for that category. When applying these parameters, &tunedapp; "
"might use the <command>sysctl</command> under the hood. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1728
