#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1935
#, no-c-format
msgid "Best practices for changing <literal>sysctl</literal> settings"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1936
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Optimal sysctl settings can vary greatly depending on the specific use case, "
"hardware and workload of your system. It is recommended to test changes "
"thoroughly and monitor system performance after applying new sysctl "
"configurations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1945
#, no-c-format
msgid "sysfs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1947
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>sysfs</literal> plug-in accepts any valid file path under the "
"system file system, or the <filename>/sys/</filename> directory. The plug-in "
"checks whether a file path is valid and can read and write the values in the "
"files that are part of the configuration. For example, consider the "
"following configuration of the <literal>sysfs</literal> plug-in:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1955
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>sysfs</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1956
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[sysfs]\n"
"/sys/bus/workqueue/devices/writeback/cpumask = 2,6 <co xml:id=\"non-isolated-"
"cpu-mask-value\"/>\n"
"/sys/devices/virtual/workqueue/cpumask = 3-5 <co xml:id=\"non-isolated-cpu-"
"mask-range\"/>\n"
"/sys/devices/system/machinecheck/machinecheck*/ignore_ce = 1 <co xml:"
"id=\"ignore-ce\"/>\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1965
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Single CPUs separated by comma. Only those CPUs that are not isolated using "
"the <parameter>isolcpus</parameter> kernel boot parameter are allowed. To "
"check the CPUs that are already isolated, run the <command>grep isolcpus /"
"proc/cmdline</command> command. To check the total number of CPUs in your "
"system, run the <command>lscpu | grep \"^CPU(s):\"</command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1974
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Range of CPUs. Only those CPUs that are not isolated using the "
"<parameter>isolcpus</parameter> kernel boot parameter are allowed. To check "
"the CPUs that are already isolated, run the command <command>grep isolcpus /"
"proc/cmdline</command> . To check the total number of CPUs in your system, "
"run the <command>lscpu | grep \"^CPU(s):\"</command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1983
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Corrected Errors (CEs) are hardware errors that the system has detected and "
"corrected automatically. The <literal>ignore_ce</literal> attribute is a "
"sysfs setting that controls whether the system must report these corrected "
"errors. When <literal>ignore_ce</literal> is set to <literal>1</literal> , "
"the system ignores corrected errors, meaning they are not logged or reported "
"to the operating system's error handling mechanisms. When "
"<literal>ignore_ce</literal> is set to <literal>0</literal> (the default "
"value), corrected errors are reported and logged by the system, allowing "
"administrators to monitor them."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1998
#, no-c-format
msgid "systemd"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2000
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>systemd</literal> plug-in focuses on configuring the parameters "
"of &systemd;, which is the system and service manager for &sles;. For "
"example, consider the plug-in configuration for CPU affinity of &systemd; "
"processes:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2006
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>systemd</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2007
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[systemd]\n"
"cpu_affinity=0,1,2 <co xml:id=\"systemd-plugin-cpu-affinity\"/>\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2013
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Binds the systemd services to multiple specified CPU cores. By default, it "
"is <literal>None</literal> . In this example, the services are configured to "
"run on CPU cores <literal>0</literal> , <literal>1</literal> , and "
"<literal>2</literal> . Alternate ways of passing the values include passing "
"a range of CPU cores, such as <literal>0-2</literal> . However, you "
"<emphasis>cannot</emphasis> pass on the CPU cores as values which you have "
"declared as <parameter>isolated_cores</parameter> in the file <filename>/etc/"
"tuned/cpu-partitioning-variables.conf</filename> . Configuring the "
"<parameter>cpu_affinity</parameter> parameter in the plug-in is equivalent "
"to configuring the <parameter>CPUAffinity</parameter> in the &systemd; "
"configuration file <filename>/etc/systemd/system.conf</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2032
#, no-c-format
msgid "script"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2034
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>script</literal> plug-in allows users to execute custom scripts "
"that &tunedapp; runs at different stages. System administrators can use it "
"to automate several system configurations and optimizations by specifying "
"paths to such scripts. Common parameters and their possible values include "
"the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2042
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>priority</parameter> : An integer value that sets the priority "
"level for the script. &tunedapp; executes scripts based on their priority, "
"with lower numbers indicating higher priority. So, a priority of <literal>5</"
"literal> means this script has a low priority compared to scripts with a "
"priority number lower than <literal>5</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2051
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>script</parameter> : This specifies the path to the script that "
"&tunedapp; executes. You can either provide the absolute path to the script "
"as its value, or use the <varname>PROFILE_DIR</varname> variable to pass the "
"relative path to the script."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2059
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, consider the following use of a relative script path:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2063
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using variables for including a relative script path in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2064
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[script]\n"
"priority=5\n"
"script=${i:PROFILE_DIR}/script.sh\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2071
#, no-c-format
msgid "Resource for definition of variables"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2072
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For a list of useful variables, inspect the constants defined in the source "
"file <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/redhat-performance/tuned/blob/"
"&tunedver;/tuned/consts.py\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2080
#, no-c-format
msgid "scheduler"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2082
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>scheduler</literal> plug-in is used to manage the isolation of "
"CPU cores and the selection of processes for management based on adding to "
"an approved list or a blocklist. This plug-in is primarily concerned with "
"isolating specific CPU cores and managing which processes should or should "
"not be managed by the scheduler. Commonly used parameters and their possible "
"values include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2091
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>isolated_cores</parameter> : Isolates specific CPU cores from the "
"general scheduler. Processes can be pinned to these isolated cores to ensure "
"they run without interference from other system processes. To pass values to "
"this parameter, use comma-separated integers representing the cores, or the "
"bitmask of the integers in the hexadecimal format. For example, "
"<literal>isolated_cores=0,1</literal> can also be represented by "
"<literal>0x3</literal> in a more compact manner."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2102
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>ps_whitelist</parameter> : A list of allowed process names that "
"the scheduler plug-in is empowered to manage. Only processes matching this "
"pattern are considered for scheduling adjustments. Pass regular expressions "
"of process names as values to this parameter. For example, <literal>.*</"
"literal> matches all processes, and <literal>^bash$</literal> matches only "
"the <literal>bash</literal> process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2112
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>ps_blacklist</parameter> : A list of process names that the plug-"
"in excludes from management. Processes matching this pattern are not "
"adjusted by the plug-in. Pass regular expressions of process names as values "
"to this parameter. For example, <literal>.*</literal> matches all processes, "
"and <literal>^idle$</literal> matches only the <literal>idle</literal> "
"process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2121
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, consider the following configuration for the "
"<literal>scheduler</literal> plug-in:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2126
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>scheduler</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2127
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"isolated_cores=0x3\n"
"ps_whitelist=.*\n"
"ps_blacklist=^idle$;.*pmd.*;.*PMD.*;^DPDK;.*qemu-kvm.*\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2136
#, no-c-format
msgid "bootloader"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2138
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>bootloader</literal> plug-in is used to apply performance "
"profiles that require changes to the boot parameters of the system. These "
"changes are made in the boot loader configuration file (typically &grub; "
"configuration) and are applied when the system boots up. This plug-in is "
"particularly useful for optimizing system performance by setting specific "
"kernel parameters, such as those controlling CPU isolation or power "
"management, as well as other boot-time settings that can affect the overall "
"system behavior and performance."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2147
#, no-c-format
msgid "Common parameters and their values are summarized below:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2152
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>grub2_cfg_file</parameter> : Specifies the &grub; configuration "
"file to modify. If not provided, the plug-in uses the default GRUB2 "
"configuration files located in the system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2159
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>initrd_dst_img</parameter> : Sets the destination path for the "
"initrd image. If specified, the initrd image is copied to this location. The "
"path must be absolute, and if it is not provided, the default boot directory "
"is used."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2166
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>initrd_add_img</parameter> : Adds the path to an initrd image in "
"the &grub; configuration, so that custom initrd images can be used during "
"the boot process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2173
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>initrd_add_dir</parameter> : Adds a directory to be included in "
"the initrd image. This parameter specifies the path to a directory whose "
"contents are packaged into an initrd image and included in the boot "
"configuration. This is useful for adding custom modules or scripts to the "
"initrd."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2181
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>initrd_remove_dir</parameter> : A boolean option to specify "
"whether to remove the directory specified in <parameter>initrd_add_dir</"
"parameter> after it has been packaged into the initrd image. If set to "
"<literal>True</literal> , the source directory is deleted after the initrd "
"image is created."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2189
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>cmdline</parameter> : Specifies additional kernel command-line "
"parameters to be added to the &grub; configuration. This allows the addition "
"of custom kernel parameters that can optimize system performance or behavior "
"based on the specific needs of the workload."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2197
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"As an example, consider the following configuration for the "
"<literal>bootloader</literal> plug-in:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2202
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>bootloader</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2203
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"[bootloader]\n"
"cmdline=\"isolcpus=1-3 nohz_full=1-3 intel_pstate=disable\"\n"
"initrd_add_img=\"/path/to/custom-initrd.img\"\n"
"initrd_add_dir=\"/path/to/custom-initrd-dir\"\n"
"initrd_remove_dir=True\n"
"initrd_dst_img=\"/boot/initrd-custom.img\"\n"
"grub2_cfg_file=\"/etc/grub2.cfg\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2216
#, no-c-format
msgid "net"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2218
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>net</literal> plug-in is used to configure several parameters "
"for optimizing network performance. Common parameters and their values used "
"with this plug-in are summarized below:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2225
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>devices</parameter> : Specifies a comma-separated list of the "
"network device names. For example, <literal>devices=eth0,eth1</literal> . By "
"default, the settings are applied on all network devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2232
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>dynamic</parameter> : Boolean values ( <literal>true</literal> / "
"<literal>false</literal> ) that enable or disable dynamic tuning based on "
"network load."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2239
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>wake_on_lan</parameter> : Configure Wake-on-LAN (WoL) settings "
"using any combination of the following characters:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2245
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>p</literal> : Wake on PHY activity."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2250
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>u</literal> : Wake on unicast messages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2255
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>m</literal> : Wake on multicast messages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2260
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>b</literal> : Wake on broadcast messages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2265
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>a</literal> : Wake on ARP."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2270
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>g</literal> : Wake on MagicPacket <superscript>TM</superscript> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2275
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>s</literal> : Enable SecureOn <superscript>TM</superscript> for "
"MagicPacket <superscript>TM</superscript> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2281
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>d</literal> : Disable WoL."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2288
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>nf_conntrack_hashsize</parameter> : Integer value setting the "
"size of the connection-tracking hash table."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2294
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>features</parameter> : A dictionary of network device feature "
"names and their desired states. For example, <literal>tx-checksum: off, sg: "
"on</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2300
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<parameter>coalesce</parameter> : A dictionary of packet coalescing "
"parameters."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2305
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
